Fred Barasa has been appointed Taita-Taveta University vice-chancellor.  Prof Barasa has been acting since 2018 after then acting Principal Hamadi Boga left to join the government. Prof Boga is now the Principal Secretary, Agriculture and Research.  Speaking yesterday during the university's fourth graduation ceremony, which was held virtually, Prof Barasa said the institution has become a centre of excellence for Mining and Fuels.  “The university is committed to building capacity in Mining and Mineral Process Engineering to both genders. Special emphasis has been put to ensure higher participation of women in our programmes,” he said.  The VC said emphasis is also given to entrepreneurial skills, which will ensure that graduates from the programme are capable of establishing small and medium enterprises to serve local, regional and international clientele.  Education CS gets back the power to appoint VCs, DVCs  Mt Kenya University install a new VC  Varsities must open virtually in September, Ministry says  Kenyan appointed Vice-Chancellor of South African University Prof Boga congratulated the new VC, saying he will take the institution to great heights of development.  “The appointment is a great step for the university, which has grown and the infrastructural development can be seen.” said Boga.    Take a quick survey and help us improve our website!     Kabarak University Vice-Chancellor Henry Kiplagat  UON students demand resignation of vice-chancellor Peter Mbithi over corruption  UON Vice-Chancellor-Peter Mbithi welcomes investigations by IPOA over students brutality By Joackim Bwana | 1 day ago By Kamau Muthoni | 2 days ago By Jane Mugambi | 3 days ago By Weldon Kipkemoi | 3 days ago Read The Standard uninterrupted with no advertisements